.
 In addition to the cost of lives, the economic impact of cancer is also
 staggering.
 It is estimated that the the premature deaths and disabilities caused by
 the disease costs more than 900 billion US dollars each year, which is
 more than 1.5% of the global gross domestic product, without accounting
 the direct medical expenses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AmericanCancerSociety2010"

\end_inset

.
 In consequence, cancer is a prioritary objective for several companies
 and governments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This disease is biologically characterized by uncontrolled cellular reproduction.
 This errant growth is caused by multiple internal and external factors
 --some of which are known and others remain unknown-- that affect cellular
 self-control mechanisms.
 When cancerous cells appear, they grow and reproduce incessantly, thus
 leading to the formation of tumors that may affect an organ or organism
 by causing sickness, loss of sensation or cognitive abilities, pain, organ
 malfunction, and sometimes death 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "National2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Breast cancer is the leading type among all cancers.
 It is one of the most frequent, and the one with the highest absolute mortality
 in the world.
 In 2012, 1.7 million new cases were reported worldwide, accounting for 26%
 of all cancers in women excluding non-melanoma skin cancer.
 Global mortality was estimated above 500 thousand deaths, representing
 14% of all cancer-related deaths in women 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ferlay2013"

\end_inset

.
 An important observation about this type of cancer is its incidence variation
 across the world: more developed regions have a higher incidence of breast
 cancer than less developed regions at a 3.4 ratio as shown in Figure 
