\begin_layout Standard
Breast cancer is an heterogeneous disease in various levels.
 Different types of breast cancer have been identified based on the structure
 where it originated and how it grows and interact with surrounding tissue.
 Each type has a variety of characteristics and symptoms that may or not
 be present in all the individuals, and each type responds differently to
 available therapies.
 Furthermore, at a genetic level, there are molecular cancer subtypes which
 can also determine the course of the disease and its response to treatment
 and are not entirely understood.
