\begin_layout Standard
The causes of breast cancer are not entirely identified.
 Different studies have associated genetic, environmental, and behavioral
 factors with the disease 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Knaul2009"

\end_inset

.
 Given the complexity of the illness, it is difficult to detect or treat
 in a generalized way, and requires costly efforts to provide early detection
 and personalized treatment.
 In general, it is widely accepted that early detection of breast cancer
 decreases its mortality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ng2003,JinshanTang2009"

\end_inset

.
 Current prompt discovery techniques contribute to the high survival rates
 (80-90%) in developed regions, and improving these methods is still a matter
 of scientific interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among the non-invasive detection methods, it is generally accepted that
 x-ray mammography is the most effective detecting breast cancer before
 it becomes clinically palpable for non-symptomatic patients 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ng2003"

\end_inset

.
 This imaging modality enables two different examination methods: screening,
 and diagnostic mammography.
 Screening mammography is a standardized study in which chraniocaudal (CC)
 and mediolateral oblique (MLO) projections are acquired from each breast.
 The images are then inspected by a trained radiologist with the aim to
 detect subtle signs that hint towards the presence of an early stage tumor.
 Some important signs of malignancy that can be detected with x-ray mammography
 include calcifications, localized parenchymal distortions, and abnormal
 tissue density.
 Screening mammography has proven to increase the cancer detection rate
 and reduce morbidity and mortality rates in the United States 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ng2003,JinshanTang2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, detection of abnormalities in screening mammography is a repetitive
 and fatiguing task, which affect the performance of the radiologists over
 a workday.
 The rate of malignant cases in screening is between 0.3% to 0.4%, or 1 every
 250 inspections.
 It has been estimated that radiologists fail to detect between 10% to 30%
 of true positive cases.
 The low sensitivity may be due to inexperience, work overload, temporary
 distractions, subtlety of the lesions or fatigue, along with the small
 frequency of cancer cases in screening.
 It has been determined that screening mammography has a positive predictive
 value -true positive rate- of less than 35% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sampat2005computer"

\end_inset

.
 This means that for every 100 biopsies ordered for suspected malignancy,
 at much 35 are found to be of malignant lesions.
 At these rates, there is a great opportunity for increasing detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some solutions have been proposed to increase the efficiency of X-ray mammograph
y.
 The most widely used is double reading, which requires a second radiologist
 to interpret the image.
 This approach increases sensitivity (true positive) and specificity (true
 negatives), but it also increases workload and costs for healthcare systems
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown1996"

\end_inset

.
 Another solution is the use of computer assisted detection (CADe) methods.
 These systems analyze each image and using tuned algorithms, place a mark
 on all suspicious regions found, which then are prompted to be evaluated
 by a radiologist.
 There is no clear evidence, however, showing an overall significant advantage
 of using CADe for screening on a clinical setting 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fenton2011"

\end_inset

.
 However, CADe also increases the workload to the radiologist because the
 mammograms need to be inspected subsequently to the computed assistance,
 to inspect each mark and determine whether the output of the CADe system
 is sufficient to change the diagnosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shile2001changes"

\end_inset

.
 Modern CADe platforms rely on the analysis of large sets of image features,
 a field of study that has been labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radiomics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 due to its similarity to other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

omics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that use big volumes of biological information to find patterns associated
 to a disease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The opportunity to improve CADe systems, and develop automated systems parallel
 to CADe is latent.
 For example, high volume screening facilities could benefit from triaging
 systems that identify high-risk mammograms prior to the inspection of the
 radiologist.
 Another opportunity relies on the ability to relate image features with
 biological phenomena happening in the mammary tissue, an aspect not covered
 by any CAD system available today.
 Furthermore, the technological capabilities of modern computers and networks
 allows the implementation of complex image analysis and artificial intelligence
 techniques to address the aforementioned opportunity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent scientific publications point towards the need to develop high-throughput
 image analysis systems that enable the characterization of image-based
 biomarkers for many diseases, including breast cancer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FDA2006,Elshinawy2010,BiomarkersinImaging"

\end_inset

.
 A biomarker is a quantitative and objective measurement that can be used
 as an indicator of a disease or physiological states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FDA2006"

\end_inset

.
 For example, blood pressure is a surrogate biomarker of adverse cardiovascular
 outcome.
 In recent years significant efforts have been made towards the identification
 of image-based biomarkers therapeutic response during drug development.
 In that particular scenario, an image biomarker is easier to follow in
 long term clinical trials, as opposed to invasive techniques that require
 more money and resources to be tracked.
 Furthermore, image based biomarkers are of special interest in cases where
 invasive techniques are non desirable, for example as replacement for the
 extraction of brain biopsies or mammary gland biopsies.
 Modern imaging equipment and digital technologies facilitate the acquisition
 of large volumes of data for discovery of image biomarkers, additionally
 the widespread availability of equipment allows the creation of the systematic
 image collections required for biomarker discovery [REF NCIA], and searching
 for correlations with other equally big sets of biological information.
 This research area that associates imaging phenotypes with other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

omics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (commonly gene expression) is referred in recent literature as radiogenomics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal objective of this dissertation is to study and contribute
 towards a better understanding of the relation between tissue structure
 in mammograms characterized with image analysis techniques, and the molecular
 status of the cells of breast cancer tumors.
 This will be done by the construction of image-based biomarkers for the
 distinction of different classes of interest: Cancer/Normal, Low/High BIRADS,
 genetic signatures of breast cancer, and molecular subtypes.
 The biomarkers will be characterized using a broad set of quantitative
 analysis techniques, emphasizing in a novel set of features obtained from
 the Minkowski functionals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A secondary objective is to create a collection of digital mammograms from
 Mexican patients, along with their corresponding demographic, clinical,
 and pathological information.
 This effort has been funded by CONACYT with the project 12345678, that
 aims to find correlations between imaging features and genetic signatures
 of breast cancer in Mexican patients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analyses performed for this dissertation part from the hypotheses that:
 image-based biomarkers derived from screening mammograms are strongly associate
d with the presence of breast cancer, and its characteristics such as BIRADS
 score or molecular subtype; and that high-order texture features have stronger
 ability to characterize breast cancer than first-order image features.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By enabling a better comprehension of the relationships between mammograms
 and breast cancer, it is expected from this research to contribute to the
 advancement of scientific knowledge in the fields of radiomics, radiogenomics,
 and breast cancer research.
\end_layout

